[The veterinarian in the article is correct. People do seem to have let their guard down. In many states the cases of WNV decreased when horse owners were vaccinating. But sadly, the vaccination rate decreased, mosquitoes and WNV increased and the number of positive WNV cases in horses has increased.

Caring for an animal means getting all the necessary vaccinations, which include the Eastern and Western equine encephalitis vaccines, West Nile virus vaccine (these are usually in combination and therefore only one injection) and tetanus. It should be repeated approximately 3 weeks to 30 days after the 1st injection. What a simple and easy way to protect your companion!

California is located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2792398,204. - Mod.TG]
